phases.content:
Single-component change to `apps/desktop/src/components/terminal/TerminalSearch.tsx` (+ its CSS, + a new test file). `@xterm/addon-search`'s `ISearchOptions` already exposes `regex?: boolean` — the addon does the work; the UI just needs to expose and forward the flag.

### Change 1 — new exported helper `isValidRegex`

Mirror the existing `formatMatchCount` / `isNoMatch` exported-for-test pattern at the top of the file:

```ts
// Exported for unit testing. A regex search term that won't compile must not
// throw out of the debounced effect — callers pre-validate with this.
export function isValidRegex(query: string): boolean {
  if (!query) return true; // empty query is a no-op search, not an error
  try {
    new RegExp(query);
    return true;
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}
```

### Change 2 — `useRegex` state + `regexError` state

Alongside `caseSensitive` (local `useState`, not persisted to a settings store — the issue's "persist alongside the case-sensitivity setting" means *handled the same way as* case-sensitivity, which is per-mount local state):

```ts
const [useRegex, setUseRegex] = useState(false);
const [regexError, setRegexError] = useState(false);
```

### Change 3 — debounced effect forwards `regex` and guards invalid patterns

Add `useRegex` to the dependency array. Inside the debounced callback, when regex mode is on, pre-validate before touching the addon:

```ts
if (useRegex && !isValidRegex(query)) {
  setRegexError(true);
  setFound(false);
  return; // do not call the addon with an uncompilable pattern
}
setRegexError(false);
const result = searchAddon.findNext(query, { caseSensitive, regex: useRegex, incremental: false });
setFound(result);
```

The `query === ""` early-return branch must also `setRegexError(false)`.

### Change 4 — forward `regex` from the other two call sites

`handleInputKeyDown` (Enter / Shift+Enter) and the ▲/▼ button `onClick`s all call `findNext` / `findPrevious` with `{ caseSensitive }` — extend each to `{ caseSensitive, regex: useRegex }`.

### Change 5 — the `.*` toggle button

Directly before the `Aa` button, same `terminal-search-btn` markup, label `.*`:

```tsx
<button
  type="button"
  className={`terminal-search-btn${useRegex ? " terminal-search-btn--active" : ""}`}
  onClick={() => setUseRegex((v) => !v)}
  title={useRegex ? "Regex (on)" : "Regex (off)"}
  aria-pressed={useRegex}
>
  .*
</button>
```

### Change 6 — invalid-pattern indicator

Reuse the existing `--no-match` red-border treatment. `inputClass` becomes `isNoMatch(found, query) || regexError`. The count span renders `regexError ? "Invalid regex" : formatMatchCount(found, query)`. No new CSS needed — `.terminal-search-input--no-match` and `.terminal-search-count` already cover it.

### Change 7 — new test file `TerminalSearch.test.ts`

The component has no test today despite exporting helpers specifically for testing (per `apps/desktop/README.md` convention). Add `apps/desktop/src/components/terminal/TerminalSearch.test.ts` with vitest cases for `formatMatchCount`, `isNoMatch`, and the new `isValidRegex` (valid pattern, invalid pattern `"["`, empty string).

### Scope boundaries
- No new dependencies, no `package.json` / lockfile changes — `regex` is already in the installed `@xterm/addon-search` typings.
- `caseSensitive` is intentionally NOT migrated to persistent storage; matching its existing local-state handling keeps the change minimal and the two toggles consistent.
- No change to `Terminal.tsx` or the search-overlay open/close wiring.
